additional_information:
Rainfall, Soil Moisture, Groundwater Level and Soil Water Potential, Air, Soil Temperature
About 5 m downslope from the north rim of the drainage hollow and is 65 cm deep. The top of hard material (bedrock or till) was about 70 cm deep, but there was free water at a depth of about 50-55 cm. Material throughout the depth of the hole was moist sandy silty clay of a gelatinous consistency. Color ranged from orange-brown to dark brown. Very few stones were present. These soils were interpreted as transported/mixed, weathered volcanic ash (Jacqueline Foss, USDA Forest Service, personal communication, 2019). The SP2 sensor array consists of soil moisture sensors at 25 and 40 cm depth, and a pressure transducer lying on the bottom of the hole, with a port at about 60 cm depth.

additional_information:
The Coastal-Marine Automated Network (C-MAN) is a meteorological observation network along the coastal United States. Consisting of about sixty stations installed on lighthouses, at capes and beaches, on near shore islands, and on offshore platforms, the stations record atmospheric pressure, wind direction, speed and gust, and air temperature; however, some C-MAN stations are designed to also measure sea surface temperature, water level, waves, relative humidity, precipitation, and visibility.

The network is maintained by the National Data Buoy Center (NDBC) of the National Weather Service (NWS), which is part of National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA), and data is ingested into numerical weather prediction computer models. It was created in the early 1980s to maintain observations that were about to be discontinued by other programs. Data is processed and transmitted similarly to the moored buoy system.

In 2002, C-MAN was added to the NOAA Observing System Architecture (NOSA).

device_specific_details:
The data are posted to our website as a .csv file, which updates every 15 minutes, and are pulled by MesoWest and many other interested groups.
No API
Sampling rate for weather variables vary, but all our weather station data are reported and updated on a quarterly hour basis.
Establishment times vary. All stations are remote and typically require helicopter access. All stations operate continuously unless issue are encountered (destruction from animals, weather, avalanches, etc.). Stations are repaired/maintained as funds and time allow.

project: Navy Oceanographic Meteorological Automatic Device (NOMAD) buoy
device_specific_details: Unknown
Camera: East (70 degrees) and South (190 degrees)

additional_information:
"The Coastal-Marine Automated Network (C-MAN) is a meteorological observation network along the coastal United States. Consisting of about sixty stations installed on lighthouses, at capes and beaches, on near shore islands, and on offshore platforms, the stations record atmospheric pressure, wind direction, speed and gust, and air temperature; however, some C-MAN stations are designed to also measure sea surface temperature, water level, waves, relative humidity, precipitation, and visibility.

The network is maintained by the National Data Buoy Center (NDBC) of the National Weather Service (NWS), which is part of National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA), and data is ingested into numerical weather prediction computer models. It was created in the early 1980s to maintain observations that were about to be discontinued by other programs. Data is processed and transmitted similarly to the moored buoy system.

In 2002, C-MAN was added to the NOAA Observing System Architecture (NOSA)."
